# Study Guide: Digital and Analog Transmission

## Table of Contents
- [Introduction](#introduction)
- [Manchester Encoding](#manchester-encoding)
- [Bipolar Schemes](#bipolar-schemes)
- [Data Communication System](#data-communication-system)
- [Circuits, Channels & Multichanneling](#circuits-channels--multichanneling)
- [Modulation of Digital Signals](#modulation-of-digital-signals)
- [Data Rate and Baud Rate](#data-rate-and-baud-rate)
- [Carrier Signal](#carrier-signal)
- [Amplitude Shift Keying (ASK)](#amplitude-shift-keying-ask)
- [Frequency Shift Keying (FSK)](#frequency-shift-keying-fsk)
- [Phase Shift Keying (PSK)](#phase-shift-keying-psk)

---

## Introduction

This study guide covers fundamental concepts related to **Digital and Analog Transmission**, including encoding schemes, modulation techniques, and data communication systems. These topics are crucial for understanding how data is transmitted across networks and communication links.

---

## Manchester Encoding

### Overview
Manchester encoding ensures **no DC component** and prevents **baseline wandering** by ensuring a **transition within each bit interval**.

### Key Points:

| Feature                     | Description                                                                 |
|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Transition                 | Occurs within each bit interval                                            |
| Voltage Levels             | Alternating between +V and -V                                             |
| First Bit                  | Starts from -V if previous signal was positive                            |
| Minimum Bandwidth          | Twice that of NRZ                                                         |

### Example
For data "010011", the first bit "0" starts from -V due to the transition from a positive signal.

---

## Bipolar Schemes

### Overview
Bipolar schemes use **three voltage levels**: **positive, negative, and zero**. One bit is represented by **zero voltage**, while the other alternates between **positive and negative**.

#### Types:

| Scheme       | Description                                                                 |
|--------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| AMI (Alternate Mark Inversion) | 0 → Zero voltage; 1 → Alternating positive/negative                      |
| Pseudoternary | 1 → Zero voltage; 0 → Alternating positive/negative                       |

> **Example:** Data = 010010 → Encoded using pseudoternary.

---

## Data Communication System

### Overview
The data communication system integrates **analog and digital** components to enable effective data transfer across various network segments.

### Components:

| Component               | Description                                                                 |
|------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| PC to Modem            | Uses **binary signal**                                                      |
| Modem to CTO           | Uses **modulated analog signal**                                           |
| CTO to Another CTO     | Uses **digital signal via TDM**                                             |
| CTO to PC              | Converts modulated signal back to binary                                   |

> **Figure 9** illustrates the integration of analog and digital components in a data communication system.

---

## Circuits, Channels & Multichanneling

### Definition
A **circuit** is a physical or logical path between **two or more points** that allows signals (analog, digital, or binary) to travel.

### Multichanneling
Multiple circuits can share the **same communication link** to increase efficiency.

> **Figure 10** shows different techniques for digital-to-analog conversion.

---

## Modulation of Digital Signals

### Overview
To transmit digital data over **bandpass channels**, we use **modulation techniques** such as:

- **Amplitude Shift Keying (ASK)**
- **Frequency Shift Keying (FSK)**
- **Phase Shift Keying (PSK)**

These techniques alter one characteristic (amplitude, frequency, or phase) of the analog carrier signal based on the **input digital data**.

---

## Data Rate and Baud Rate

### Definitions

| Term         | Description                                                                 |
|--------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Bit Rate     | Number of **bits** transmitted per second                                  |
| Baud Rate    | Number of **signal units** (symbols) transmitted per second                |

### Relationship:
$$ \text{Bit Rate} = \text{Baud Rate} \times (\text{Number of bits per symbol}) $$

> **Note:** Bit rate is always greater than or equal to baud rate.

---

## Carrier Signal

### Role
The **carrier signal** is a **high-frequency** sinusoidal signal used to **modulate** the digital data. It acts as a base signal whose **amplitude, frequency, or phase** is altered to encode the digital data.

> Advantages:
- Efficient transmission
- Smaller antenna size due to higher frequency

---

## Amplitude Shift Keying (ASK)

### Overview
- **Strength of carrier** varies to represent **binary 0 and 1**
- **Frequency and phase** remain constant
- Used in early modems

### Formula:
$$ y(t) = f(t) \times \sin(2\pi f_c t + \phi) $$
Where:
- $f_c$: Carrier frequency
- $\phi$: Phase angle

### Disadvantages:
- Susceptible to **noise interference**
- Limited **amplitude change rate**

---

## Frequency Shift Keying (FSK)

### Overview
- **Frequency** of the carrier changes depending on the **input data** (bit value)
- **Amplitude and phase** remain constant

### Formula:
$$ y(t) = f_1(t)\sin(2\pi f_{c1}t + \phi) + f_2(t)\sin(2\pi f_{c2}t + \phi) $$
Where:
- $f_{c1}, f_{c2}$: Different carrier frequencies for '0' and '1'

### Bandwidth:
$$ BW = \text{Baud Rate} + \Delta f $$

> **Advantages:**
- Better noise resistance than ASK
- Used in **low-speed modems** (up to 1200 baud)

---

## Phase Shift Keying (PSK)

### Overview
- **Phase** of the carrier signal changes based on the input data
- **Amplitude and frequency** remain constant

### Binary PSK (2-PSK):
- '0': 0° phase
- '1': 180° phase

### Advantages:
- Immune to **noise**
- Not constrained by **bandwidth limits**

### Disadvantage:
- Requires **phase synchronization** at the receiver

---

## Differential Phase Modulation

### Overview
A type of **phase modulation** where the **phase of successive symbols** changes relative to the previous one.

> **Example:** 0 → 90°, 1 → 270° (illustrated in **Figure 13**)

---

## Summary Table

| Concept               | Description                                                                 |
|----------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Manchester Encoding  | Ensures no DC component and baseline wandering                             |
| Bipolar Schemes      | Use three voltage levels (positive, negative, zero)                        |
| Data Communication   | Combines analog and digital signals to achieve full communication          |
| Modulation Techniques| ASK, FSK, PSK are methods to convert digital to analog signals              |
| Baud vs Bit Rate     | Bit rate is generally greater than or equal to baud rate                   |
| Carrier Signal       | High-frequency signal used for modulation                                 |

---

## Diagram: Phase Shift Keying (PSK)

```text
        |
        v
     _________
    |         |
    |   0°    | <--- 0
    |_________|
        |
        v
     _________
    |         |
    |   180°  | <--- 1
    |_________|
```

> This diagram represents **Binary PSK** where a **0°** phase corresponds to a '0' and **180°** phase corresponds to a '1'.

---

## Conclusion

Understanding the principles of **Manchester encoding**, **bipolar schemes**, **modulation techniques**, and **data communication systems** is essential for grasping how data is efficiently and reliably transmitted over modern networks. These concepts underpin the functionality of **modems**, **telecom infrastructure**, and **wireless communication protocols**.
```

